pr_review_comment_body:
Intended, for cases like:

```c++
auto my_lambda = [](){
  do_stuff();
};
```

My thought on the other approach was to do something like this:

    ThJobArtifactModel.get_list({job_id: $scope.job_id, name__in: 'text_log_summary, Job Info'})
    .then(function(artifactList) {
        artifactList.forEach(function(artifact) {
            if (artifact.name === "text_log_summary") {
                $scope.artifact = artifact.blob;
            } else if (artifact.name === "Job Info") {
                $scope.job_details = artifact.blob.job_details;
            }
        });
    });

That removes the brittle-ness and makes for a single AJAX call.

There are a few ways to approach this situation with the log links, but here's one:

Outside this function, declare a $scope var like this:

    $scope.checkedLogLinks = {
        parsedLog: $scope.parsedLog,
        fullLog: $scope.fullLog,
        reftest: $scope.reftest
    };

Then in the html for each ``<input>`` remove the ``checked=true`` part and add  this:

    ng-model="checkedLogLinks.parsedLog"
    ng-true-value="'{{parsedLog}}'"/>

changing as appropriate for each check.  This will keep track of the desired log links in the $scope variable of ``checkedLogLinks``.  It'll save the actual text of the links in there for easy retrieval.   Then, replace the next for loop with something like this:

    var logstrings = _.reduce($scope.checkedLogLinks, function(result, link) {
        if(link) {
            result = result + link + "\n\n";
        }
        return result;
    }, "");

I know this doesn't really make the code much shorter or anything, but it's easier to read and follow, I think.  :)

The following would be a good start:

```js
expect(displayPrecision('123.53222')).toEqual('123.53');
expect(displayPrecision(1/0)).toEqual('N/A');
```

I'm now realizing that this vector doesn't need to exist here either. We could just combine the 2 loops and avoid having to create this vector.

In other words, we could replace this line with:

~~~c++
Real targetDensity = localActivityDensity / numNeighbors;
Real boostFactor = exp(-(activeDutyCycles_[i] - targetDensity) * maxBoost_);

// Avoid floating point mismatches between implementations.
boostFactors_[i] = round(boostFactor * 100.0) / 100.0;
~~~

Possible other way to handle this instead of checking for "hex" attribute:

    try:
        # Python3
        return ET.tostring(self.element(), encoding='unicode')
    except LookupError:
        # Python 2
        return ET.tostring(self.element())

The returned string is of type 'str' for both python2 and python3.  Not sure if this is better or worse, up to you.
